IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDescription: Provides housing and support services to individuals and families impacted by HIV/AIDS
IRS990.MissionDescription: Chicago House and Social Service Agency (Chicago House) was formed in 1985 to provide housing and supportive services to HIV-affected families and individuals, who may also be impacted by poverty, homelessness, substance abuse, and mental illness. (SEE SCHED. O) All Chicago House services are provided without discrimination and are explicitly designed to guide people towards wholeness and self-sufficiency.
IRS990.Description: Residential Housing - The Family Support Program offers housing, case management, and other supportive services to 18 HIV/AIDS affected families that include over 40 dependent children. Designed for families facing homelessness and poverty in addition to HIV/AIDS, the program works intensively with both the parents and the children.The Supportive Living Program is a 16-unit group living facility in Chicago's West Town neighborhood, which provides the "first step" of housing and supportive services to adults living with HIV/AIDS who come directly from the streets or the shelter system; this facility is staffed 24 hours.The Independent Living Program is a 24-unit apartment building in Uptown, providing permanent housing to adults living with HIV/AIDS in need of affordable housing with supportive services available to meet intermittent needs.

Activity2.Description: Employment - iFOUR (Increase Individual Income and Independence) In 2005, Chicago House began Chicago's first city-wide employment program for people with HIV/AIDS. The program is Designed to help unemployed adults with HIV secure and retain productive employment to ensure that they do not need to rely solely on subsidized medical care, housing, and supportive services. A four-week training workshop, career counseling, mentorship and internship opportunities are the services provided to help clients achieve greater selfsufficiency and productivity, ultimately leading to successful employment. In 2008, Sweet Miss Giving's Bakery opened offering a transitional jobs training program in the food service industry for those living with HIV.

Activity3.Description: Scattered Site Housing - The Gaining Ground Program assists homeless individuals with HIV and AIDS who struggle with substance abuse and other challenges to find stable housing and receive supportive services that focus on harm reduction to enable clients to live independently. This housing is also linked with the iFOUR Employment Program. Clients develop the skills necessary to return to work and increase their income level, moving them to greater selfsufficiency and ultimately allowing the housing subsidies to pass to others beginning the employment process.The Housing to Healthcare Partnership (HHP) is a collaborative service and researchproject that provides stable, safe housing for individuals with a chronic medical illness, such as HIV/AIDS, who are homeless or lack permanent housing. Under HHP, case managers find attainable housing for the chronically ill and homeless by locating interim housing until permanent housing becomes available or by placing clients directly into permanent housing.

ActivityOther.Description: Prevention - Be Aware, Be Alive (BABA) Traditionally, AIDS prevention has focused on those who are HIV negative, helping them to not become positive. Since 2002, Chicago House has pioneered the Prevention with Positives Initiative with one underlying principle: every new infection is contracted from someone that is already HIV impacted. If "safe" practices can be encouraged among those who are HIV positive, it can help stem the tide of AIDS while keeping those already impacted from contracting a drug resistant strain of HIV. BABA is an HIV prevention program involving two interventions: HIV prevention counseling, and HIV testing. Counseling is provided for persons living with HIV who are having difficulty maintaining safer sex or needle sharing behaviors. Factors that may impact a client's ability to maintain safer behaviors include: mental illness, homelessness or risk of homelessness, domestic violence, and substance abuse. The HIV prevention counselor works one-on-one with clients to assist them with achieving risk reduction goals. HIV rapid testing also provided. This program seeks to help identify some of the estimated 25% of individuals in the United States living with HIV who are unaware of their HIV status.

Community Case Management Program The most cost efficient way to deal with the issue of homelessness is to keep people out of the system from the start. As early as 1992, Chicago House began doing Community Case Management with people who were becoming increasingly ill with AIDS, helping them to get the support (legal, food, utility assistance) and benefits (Medicare, Medicaid, Disability) they needed to remain in their own homes and not become homeless. Today Chicago House serves over 150 men, women and children a year by providing them these needed support services in the comfort of their own home.
Miscellaneous programs related to assistance to individuals in advanced stages of AIDS.

Form990ScheduleDPartXIV.ReturnReference: Description of Uncertain Tax Positions Under FIN 48:
Form990ScheduleDPartXIV.Explanation: FIN 48 Foot Note Chicago House and Social Service Agency was granted exemption from federal income tax by the Internal Revenue Service pursuant to the provisions of Internal Revenue Code Section 501 (c)(3). The Organization qualifies for the charitable contribution deduction under Section 170 (b)(1)(A)(vi) and has been classified as an Organization that is not a private foundation under Section 509 (a)(1). The tax exempt purpose of the Organization and the nature in which it operates is described above (page 2 of Form 990). The Organization continues to operate in compliance with its tax exempt purpose. The Organization's annual informational returns filed with the federal and state governments are subject to examination for the statutory period.

Form990ScheduleIPartIII.TypeOfGrant: Client food, grocery gift cards, transportation cards, stipends, client trips,and miscellaneous household items

Form990ScheduleIPartIV.Identifier: Procedure for Monitoring Grants in the U.S.:
Form990ScheduleIPartIV.Explanation: Schedule I, Part I, Line 2: Clients or their dependents served by Chicago House must have a confirmed diagnosis of HIV+, as certified by a physician. Clients accepted into our programs can not exceed the maximum income level for "very low" income individuals or families as defined by HUD guidelines. Once the HIV+ diagnosis and income level is confirmed, individuals or families can apply for housing or support services through the agency. Background checks are performed and interviews conducted. During the interview process, Case Managers assess the needs of the client, including housing and support services. Once accepted into a Chicago House program, each client is assigned a Case Manager who is responsible for direct support of that client and on-going assessment of their needs. Annual income certification is performed by the Property Manager to ensure clients meet the required guidelines to continue to receive the services provided by the agency.

Form990ScheduleLPartIV.DescriptionOfTransaction: See Sch O - The CEO also serves as the Chief Executive Officer of Sweet Miss Giving's, NFP. (20-8834313), Sweet Miss Giving's, NFP is the General Partner of Sweet Miss Giving's Bakery, LLC (26-1318671) with a 51% partnership interest. During the year ended June 30, 2010, the Organization granted Sweet Miss Giving's NFP $298,000.

See Sch O - Sweet Miss Giving's Bakery, LLC's Bakery is used as a site for the Organization's transitional jobs program (IFOUR). During previous years, Chicago House provided for a build-out of space for the Bakery to be used as the site for its transitional jobs program - iFour. Chicago House also provided equipment and vehicles to the Bakery to be consumed by the traditional jobs program over time. The equipment and vehicles are the assets of Chicago House and are recorded in the financial statements as such at June 30, 2010. At June 30, 2010, the Organization had a receivable balance from Sweet Miss Giving's Bakery LLC for $59,270.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 11
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The 990 is reviewed and approved by the organization's Director of Finance and Administration. The Chief Executive Officer and Treasurer of the Board of Trustees review the 990 and prior to filing it is distributed to every member of the Board of Trustees.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 12c
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: At the start of every board meeting, the Chair inquires as to any new reportable conflicts of interest. Board members are encouraged to report conflicts as they arise between meetings.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, line 15
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The CEO's salary is recommended to the full Board by the Executive Committee based on comparative data, financial health of the agency and performance review. The recommendation is presented to the Board for approval. The directors salaries are recommended to the Executive Committee by the CEO based on comparative data, financial health of the agency and performance review. The Executive Committee approves or rejects the recommendations.

GeneralExplanation.Identifier: Form 990, Part VI, Section C, line 19
GeneralExplanation.Explanation: The organization makes it's governing documents, conflict of interest and financial statements available upon request.

The financial statements of the Organization were included in consolidated audited financial statements presented in conformity with U.S. Generally Accepted Accounting Principals. Separate financial statements were included in audit report for the entities consolidated in the audit.
